###############
#  compiling  #
###############

Enter the command ./build_abeeda

If the console gives an error about permissions, enter:

chmod 755 build_abeeda

then enter the above build command again.

###########
#  usage  #
###########

To evolve the swarm, enter the following command:

./abeeda EVOLVE <LOD output file> <genome output file> <make video> <swarm> <predator> <RNG seed>

EXAMPLE: ./abeeda EVOLVE ~/data/abeeda/swarm-predator/run50LOD.txt ~/data/abeeda/swarm-predator/run50genome.txt 0 1 1 50


Parameters:

LOD output file: the file to save the LOD data to at the end of the run. beware that if the provided file already exists, it will be overwritten.

genome output file: the file to save the final genome to at the end of the run. beware that if the provided file already exists, it will be overwritten.

make video: 0 (false) or 1 (true) indicating whether or not a video should be made (on the HPCC, enter 0).
IMPORTANT: if you are going to make a video, run the abeeda monitor first or you will get an error!

swarm: 0 (false) or 1 (true) indicating whether the swarm metric should be incorporated in the swarm fitness.

predator: 0 (false) or 1 (true) indicating whether the predator metric should be incorporated in the swarm fitness.

RNG seed: an integer value to seed the random number generator with. ensure this number is unique to have different results for each run.


To display a pre-evolved swarm, enter the following command:

./abeeda DISPLAY <genome file> <swarm> <predator>

EXAMPLE: ./abeeda DISPLAY ~/data/abeeda/swarm-predator/run50genome.txt 1 1

IMPORTANT: this mode is only supported on Mac OSX Lion!


Parameters:

genome file: the file that contains the pre-evolved swarm genome.

swarm: 0 (false) or 1 (true) indicating whether the swarm metric should be incorporated in the swarm fitness.

predator: 0 (false) or 1 (true) indicating whether the predator metric should be incorporated in the swarm fitness.


############
#  output  #
############

genome output: this file will contain all of the values describing the final swarm's Markov Model brain


LOD output: this file will contain all of the data on the best LOD at the end of the run.

format: sorted from oldest to newest ancestor.

one line for each update in the swarm simulation

(this is easier to read with no wrap-around)

<update 0>    <fitness at update 0>    <number prey alive at update 0>    <total swarm size> <x position of prey 1 at update 0>    <y position of prey 1 at update 0>    ... <x position of prey m at update 0>    <y position of prey m at update 0>    <x position of predator update 0>    <y position of predator at update 0>
...
<update n>    <fitness at update n>    <number prey alive at update n>    <total swarm size> <x position of prey 1 at update n>    <y position of prey 1 at update n>    ... <x position of prey m at update n>    <y position of prey m at update n>    <x position of predator update n>    <y position of predator at update n>
<update n+1>  <fitness at update n+1>  <number prey alive at update n+1>  <total swarm size> <x position of prey 1 at update n+1>  <y position of prey 1 at update n+1>  ... <x position of prey m at update n+1>  <y position of prey m at update n+1>  <x position of predator update n+1>  <y position of predator at update n+1>
...
<update 1999> <fitness at update 1999> <number prey alive at update 1999> <total swarm size> <x position of prey 1 at update 1999> <y position of prey 1 at update 1999> ... <x position of prey m at update 1999> <y position of prey m at update 1999> <x position of predator update 1999> <y position of predator at update 1999>

each LOD entry in the file is separated by an extra newline
